segments.text: We were discussing whether or not we would have changed our our approach or whether the profession should have changed their approach and what was your comment on that?

Well I started to say you know when we graduated we thought we were pretty well pretty knowledgeable and some of the old vet old vets around that been around for a while we thought they were kind of back woodsy and

I worked with Dr. Bailey and taught that old vet school back in the 1920s, 18, 1918 and all right after World War I and think about the type of practice he carried on and he carried on a pretty good, pretty smart operator and I think of what the new graduates have to go through and I think I'm
way behind time now and can't catch up.
Well, all these autoimmune diseases and so forth take a lot more knowledge than what we were exposed to then.

Of course, we've kept up with a lot of it, but wouldn't you say perhaps that since you and I graduated, they've learned about as much about animal disease since we graduated as we were exposed to in school and before?
That's right.
I think we...
Of course, I think about old that bacteriology merchant giving us all his wisdom and how much farther what we didn't know about viruses in those days, don't you?
Yes, and immunity.
Yeah, immunity and I look at the old book textbook every once in a while
I think we'll all have to admit that the advent of chick embryo vaccines really helped a lot because here they could grow it without having to have an animal.
All they needed was the eggs.
That's right.
And it's helped a lot.
See, they started that chick embryo there at St. Joe Laboratories.
I think about all the eggs and eggs and thousands and thousands of eggs that they run through that place down there on the river bottom.
The, what do you think about, I was going to ask you some questions about organized veterinary medicine, but I want to put that on a separate tape.
Let me ask you this, I feel that during our practice life, there is a possibility
that the clients have changed, and that as times have gone, we're supposed to be more intelligent and so forth, and approach to things.
Aren't clients considerably more critical and expect a whole lot more than they did when we first went into practice?
For instance, were people pleased, more easily pleased with what you could do then than even they are now?
You mean pleased now or pleased then?
Pleased then.

well if you could keep your dog alive back in those days well you're pretty pretty good you know if you didn't let it die with distemper if you kept it got it through distemper i don't know whether you went through those distemper times or not uh that we i remember them from north carolina a lot and we didn't have real active immunity and then your dog would break with that
It's not no distemper that we'd see.
It just wasn't anything you could do.
I mean, what did you fight it with?

Well, of course, whatever we used, it seems the outcome was the same as about what you said, but I felt with distemper, if you had a client that could do the nurse's dog and the dog didn't get encephalitis, you had it made.
You had it made.
You could bring...
We used to vaccinate them.
That was what the old Fox people wanted.
They wanted one that was actively immune.
He didn't want one that was going to break after you got him out and started running him.
And we put him in just what we call the distemper ward and wait till the temperature rise and try to fight him down.
That's the way we did it.
I mean, they did it.
I didn't.
I wasn't a vet.
I was just a student in a kennel band at that time.
And I remember
it's so bad it was pretty bad.
Do you recall hard pad disease in the late 40s?

I remember the hard pad disease when it hit and came supposed to have come from England and you'd get a dog on a table and you'd hear him his feet scratching the table and you just about as well kiss him goodbye as I remember it.
Now have you seen one lately?
I've seen one or two lately I mean
No, not very many.
Maybe a couple last year.
I haven't, I don't know if I've seen any this year, but I know I saw a couple last year.
We used to get, we get an awful lot of snake bites.
Get a lot of, a lot of snake bites here due to the location of our practice.
Used to get quite a few thallium poisons.
Don't see much thallium anymore.
Used to a lot of strychnine don't you think?
Yeah I see quite a few strychnine now I've had some recent poilings that I don't know whether there's somebody got any 1080 or not but I'm beginning to think we've got some 1080 floating around.
I saw a thing on TV the other night that they were getting going to get 1080 back for coyotes up in the hill country from Brown Brady I think or someplace up in there and that 1080 is a
I don't think you can do any good for it.
I never have found anything.
Do you have ever, have you ever found anything?
No, we don't have much down there, fortunately.
I got in a new poison the other day from California.
I don't know that I got it.
It's a rat poison that they use in California, and the stuff is
So toxic.
I mean, I called a veterinarian out there.
And he told me about it.
What they can't remember the name of it.
Let's see.
But it is, he said it was rough.
And he said, don't think you've got them cured until you've been a long time.
Gone by.
Let me ask you another question.
You know, when we first got into practice, we thought that the cat disease was infectious panleukopenia.
What do you think about viral diseases in cats now?
I'm kind of lost.
I'm not very up-to-date on it, I'm afraid.
I'll have to admit, I wonder when I see some of these pictures

our literature coming out and the new vaccine the calcivirus and whatnot I wonder if we haven't had that all along didn't know what we had how about you well without a doubt we had some of it before but the feline infectious anemia we had then hemobartonella also the feline infectious peritonitis with the swelled tummies we've had that for
long time, but I really think perhaps that this feline leukemia perhaps is relatively recent.
The cats just seem to get cat decline, and many of those are positive leukemia.
You found that poison?
Yeah.
What's it called?
Ramek Green.
How does that spell?
R-A-M-I-C-K.
G-R-E-E-N. And it's Velsicol KRL, is that what it's called?
Yeah, ceramic green is the name of it, I think.
And it's a...
It's not like decon, is it?
Yeah, it's a decon type thing, but he says it works.
I call it Dr. Christie in California.

He said it was very bad like decon like poisoning and the vitamin K blood transfusions and everything he said it was he had treated it though for this lady and she had moved here from California and I called and talked to him.
Well uh what other observations you have on veterinary medicine you think it's been good to you?
Been good to me I've had nothing but
I've enjoyed my practice for years.

Really, I'm probably not as good an up-to-date veterinarian as I could have been, but I think I've served the community about as well as anybody could from the standpoint of taking care of large animals, small animals in the hall.
Now, you can't be a general practitioner and do it all,

and and be an expert in in everything but uh an area that can't support a veterinarian needs a general practitioner and when you have a small animal man move in and do nothing in an area that needs this large animal man i'm kind of critical of that and i have been outspoken on it i think it's uh the day of the general practitioner they say is gone but i in the small community

you better be able to do a little of everything when these clients go to a veterinarian and he says I don't treat anything but dogs and cats and the people don't like it especially if there's nobody else who can take care of them within 100 miles but in general on large animals with the exception of horses isn't the era of the small
herd finished where you have maybe have a half dozen cows and they call you out for dystopia and whatnot that sort of thing is almost gone.
Those things are gone.
When I came to this area here I used to come in here when I was still in Corpus come into this area here and I'd test 40, 50 cows for bangs and TB and- Not all the same herd.
Well no two cows here three cows in another place five over here and I'd
have to hunt hard to find one or two milk cows right now.
There are no milk cows out.
No dairy, no small farmers.
They all get their milk out of a cardboard carton.
And your practice, as far as Lardown was, there's very little family type like we used to have.
This area used to be a rural community with lots of two or three cow people.
milk cows that milked them, but they're just not here anymore.
You'd starve to death.

But by the same token, you need somebody to take care of what cows there are and what horses there are, and we have a lot of just nothing but small animal men in the area, and they can't be a large animal man.
Now, we've got a new large animal man in the area, and he's doing very well.

keep doing small animal and large animals but we've had three and four of them in the in the general area that wouldn't wouldn't look at a cow in their backyard wouldn't help their neighbor even I've been in the backyard of the vets and the ranches and backyards of ones in Rockport and uh they just won't touch them and I I don't think it's it's right that you they better call a man 20
20 miles off when they're sitting right in his backyard.
That's the way I feel now.

If a man has to call a vet from 25, 30, 40 miles away and still has a vet in his backyard that won't treat anything because he's either not qualified or he's scared to death of large animals, you know what I'm talking about.
And they don't like it.

and I'm critical of that fact and they say well you can't do both but if he if he moves in and treats nothing but dogs and cats and the closest vet is 30 miles away and a large animal man can't make it on in that area by himself I think he's it's bad
You can't help but notice as the veterinary graduates come out of the schools now that about half the graduates are women.
Yeah.
Have you adjusted to that?
I'm not against the women veterinarians.
I just don't know whether they can do any work out in the, as much work out in the field.
They may be a cowgirl that can get out and wrestle cattle and take and do the jobs that we've done in the past.
Maybe the rancher's going to do his own OB work, do everything like that.
Maybe this woman's going out and do some of the work that I've done in the past, but I don't believe she is.
I don't think she's going out and wrassling these herds around.
Maybe she will, but I just don't believe it.
Yeah, I haven't seen it yet.
I know they do pretty good in a small animal practice.
Would you feel that obviously a lot of these women aren't staying in practice?
Do you think it's a waste of the taxpayers money in a lot of cases to uh- I saw some something some uh

research or literature or something on people women staying in practice here the other day said that the women were staying in small animal practice about as good as the large as the men were in in small animal practice uh I don't know whether that's true or not but I it was in I think the latest southwestern veterinarian talking about was that right yeah
I'll have to get that magazine.
It's over at the house.
We can let you look at it, read it.
I'd like to see that statistic.
I think it's in there.
I'm not positive, but I read a little bit at night until my eyes go bad.
Let's change the subject a little bit, and it's part of the same subject but really different.
One of the big things that veterinary medicine does
or veterinary medicine needs is enough camaraderie and enough sharing and pooling of thought and ideas so that we can help each other help the public.
When you first came from school and came down here in Corpus Christi, what was organized veterinary medicine like at that time to your way of looking at it?
There wasn't much of an organization as far as I know of.
We got maybe
We'd get together once in a while over a meal, and that was about it, and talk about it.
Who were the veterinarians at that time here in Corpus Christi who participated in that?
We had Dr. Dunn.
What were his initials?
I don't know.
I think S.E., but I'm not.
Dr. Oberg.
Oh, yes.
What were his initials?
Don't ask me those questions.
Oberg.
came down from Nebraska.
He was a real hog specialist, swine specialist up in his field and he came down here I think due to bad health and all and he practiced.
If you had a hog problem you'd call him.
I mean he was a large animal man.
Dr. Dunn was the veterinarian for from south of all south Texas so to speak.
He practiced from the
You might say Victoria to the Laredo, all of that point.
There wasn't another vent in the country.
And he covered from Victoria over towards Laredo and all of that area south of that.
And he was gone most of the time.
And then he had Dr. Fondren came in from San Antonio.
Fondren moved here.

came in to work with Dr. Dunn at that time and he had an old graduate army sergeant or whatever you want working for him at the time, Dr. Dunn did and that was all that was in Corpus except Dr. Springs Hospital.
And you all got together, did you?
We got together and talked things over and the doctor
We had a few meetings.
Then Dr. Brandes and Hoban and later Dr. Pruitt, I think we all got together and started a little meeting.
And the first organization was a meeting, I think we organized about 50.
1950 was about the first time we really called it a Coastal Bend Veterinary Group.
And that included where, from Alice and Kingsville on?
Yeah, we had Kingsville, we had Thal Fuerst, Dr. Saxton came over, Dr. Scotty out of Beeville, and Scotty McNeil, and uh, Botard, when he graduated, he went to Kingsville, and uh,
We got together maybe once a month.
We met over at Kingsville at King's Inn a couple times, and then we, usually we'd just have a meeting where we'd get together, and then I think it was, according to Hoban, we organized in about 1950.
Oh, yes.
He was first secretary, and I was first president of our group.
Was Dr. Spring there at that time?
Dr. Spring was leaving.
He left long about that time.
I had brought the hospital.
Dr. Spriggle was working for me and we'd get together and hoping Oberg would come, some, until he, you know, and we'd invite them all and try to get them to come in and
Just talk things over.
That was the first organization we had.
Brandis and Pruitt came along about that time, didn't they?
Yeah, they moved in about that time.
And they were quite active, weren't they?
They built their hospitals, and they had one, and then they moved out on the highway out there afterwards.
Yes.
Down through the years, who's been the most faithful and more or less keeping you going here in Corpus Christi?
Well, after I left, too.
Of course I left there in 56, 57 I think.
Doctor, well I know Paget has probably kept the thing going as much as anybody.
I see.
I think.
He and his wife too?
Yeah.
He sent out letters and all.
Now we've got the- What's the name of his receptionist?
Dr. Slater is that woman veterinarian, I think.
She's the secretary now.
She sends out all the notices.
And I haven't been too active recently.
I kind of slid out of it.
I went to their Christmas party this year, and that's about the last time I've been.
I just don't go much.
They have so many new veterinarians, 20 or 30 of them.
Dr. Fry moved in.
The two Frys, Dr. Fry and...
both of those are pretty active too.
And I know Dr. Scotty McNeil and I drove to Abilene to try to reorganize the state association, you know.
We had the state association meeting here one time.
Right.
Well, that was the second one, I think.
Oh, okay.
We had one before that.
Okay.
And Dr.
Grist organized it.
He was the secretary at that time.
And Dr. Blunt was active in the state association.
I don't know what he was.
Later.
Huh?
Later.
Yeah, but Dr.
Grist was the original.
He organized our first meeting in Corpus.
Yes.
came down and made all the contacts and hotels and arrangements for meeting rooms and everything else.
And he could tell you more about it than I can.
I can't remember that meeting.
Was I in the service then?
I may have been.
Probably was.
Yes.
That was the first meeting we had was in, along about that time, I think it was probably in 49, 50, right about the time we tried to reorganize after the meeting here with
I know we went to Abilene and they hired some public relations man to kick us off and whatnot.
Yes.
I don't know whether you remember that or not.
Well, I know I don't really recall that, but I, again, I may not have been here.
As far as you know, they didn't keep a set of written records here in the Coastal Bend Association, right?
So far nobody can find it.
If they did, I mean, Hoban
I was secretary at the time.
We didn't have much of an organization as far as dues or just kind of a get together to talk things over.
What was going on, you know, was all it was.
It wasn't a very fancy organization.
Now, I forgot one vet that was here that was kind of active.
It was Dr. Judson, you know.
had a pretty nice little hospital there for you.
He was pretty active.
He passed on, is that right?
Yeah, he died.
He had cancer of the throat.
Judson was...
He was born about what year, about 1920?
I imagine he was about our age, 20, and he was brought up down in Mexico by Mexican
I mean, he spoke Mexican real good, and he set up his practice there in the Port Ayers community right north of Hoban's a little ways, and he had a pretty nice little hospital, you know.
Judson did.
Yes.
What was his first name?
William.
William.
I've got it easy.
And he's been gone how many years?
He probably died in 50, 60, about 60-something.
I don't remember exactly.
I went to his funeral.
I went to his marriage when he got married.
See, he didn't get married early, and he was still... What's the current status of the Veterinary Association here?
You don't really know much about it.
I'm not active.
I know I went to the
Christmas party out at the Fry's house.
There's so many young ones and stuff, I feel kind of like a lost goose out there.
Was there a Holcomb here, you know?
There's a bunch of them in Portland, and Dr. Bauer is in Portland.
We got two or three others in Portland.
We got the one in Taft now.
go.
Dr. the real McCoy's in Senton.
Think about TDMA?
Yes.
Well I have been a member off and on and I'm not a member up in good standing right now I don't think.
I'm kind of dropped out.
I'll have to talk you into that again.
What?
I'll have to talk you into that again.
Yeah well I've been a member and Barb was
president of the TVMA Auxiliary, you know.
I was active along in there, you know, but I kind of dropped out when you don't go to meetings, and I guess you just get old.
Lazy, don't want to go.
No, I'd like to probably keep my membership.
Dr. Spring let his license expire.
Well, but he, where's he living now?
He's 72, you know, and he figured, well, I'm not going to do much practice.

He let his license, he didn't renew it in time, and, you know, just kind of one of those things that by that time his wife's real sick, and he's had a triple bypass, and he didn't get his membership in, so he's
He said, I'd kind of like to have it, but it's not that important, you know.
At this same time or on the same day, I had a telephone conversation with Dr. Martin Pigott in regard to the history of the Coastal Bend Veterinary Medical Association.
He said when he was first there, which we have discussed in regards to Dr. Haubutzel's beginning here, they started relatively informally and then it built up and built up.
to the point where they were actually having formal dinner meetings and having them program every time and so forth and then worked off after that into seminars and for three years
They had a lot of very heavy technical seminars.
They would, of course, discuss very highly technical aspects of clinical medicine and practice and so forth and so on.
Then following that, some of them more or less were burned out, not so much the dinner meeting, but they were burned out on all this technical material.

They filled their minds with a lot of things and felt that they really weren't helping their clientele a whole lot with a lot of this material, especially as regards the service they were giving their clientele.
And the meetings then became less formal.
And instead of having dinner meetings, they'd meet in a place, order off the menu if needed to do that, or just meet separately.
and became much, much less formal and they would discuss problems in regards to the management and helping their clients and so forth and so on and became less formal.
Now this increased formality began about a year ago and of course this is the year 1982.
So with that, we can see the vagaries and the fluctuations of emphasis in practice and how veterinary medicine is going to aid the public.
